ercent of the deaths.In The Guatemalan Military Project, Jennifer Schirmer documents the military's role in human rights violations through a series of extensive interviews striking in their brutal frankness and unique in their first-hand descriptions of the campaign against Guatemala's citizens. High-ranking officers explain in their own words their thoughts and feelings regarding violence, political opposition, national security doctrine, democracy, human rights, and law. Additional interviews with congressional deputies, Guatemalan lawyers, journalists, social scientists, and a former president give a full and balanced account of the Guatemalan power structure and ruling system.With expert analysis of these interviews in the context of cultural, legal, and human rights considerations, The Guatemalan Military Project provides a successful evaluation of the possibilities and processes of conversion from war to peace in Latin America and around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCivil-military relationszGuatemalaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndians of Central AmericazGuatemalaxGovernment relations. 0aPolitical persecutionzGuatemalaxHistoryy20th century. 4aCaribbean Studies. 4aHuman Rights. 4aLatin American Studies. 4aLaw. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220059140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812200591423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812200591.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  